'''Okinawa Prefecture Gokoku Shrine''' ({{nihongo|沖縄県護国神社|1=Okinawa Gokoku Shrine|Okinawaken Gokoku Jinja}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located within {{ill|Onoyama Park|ja|奥武山公園|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onoyama Park|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 沖縄県営奥武山公園}}, {{ill|Naha|en|Naha|WD=Q181966|lt=Naha|1=Naha}}, Okinawa Prefecture, Japan. The shrine is an independent religious institution not affiliated with [[:en:Jinja Honcho|Jinja Honcho]].
{{ill|Okinawa Gokoku Shrine|ja|沖縄県護国神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Gokoku Shrine|qq=}} is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|WD=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}.  It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|WD=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|WD=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

The Okinawa Gokoku-jinja Shrine also enshrines the dead of the {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|en|Battle of Okinawa|WD=Q192660|lt=Battle of Okinawa|1=Battle of Okinawa}}, including ordinary residents, schoolchildren in distress, and civilian war dead.<ref>[[護国神社#山中|山中 2013]]、212頁</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-08 |title=沖縄県護国神社について｜初詣、ご祈願、地鎮祭は、沖縄県護国神社 |url=https://www.okinawa-gokoku.jp/about.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220308190702/https://www.okinawa-gokoku.jp/about.php |archive-date=8 March 2022 |access-date=2022-03-08 |website=}}</ref> In addition, about 10,000 mobilized students and female volunteer corps members who were victims of the {{ill|Atomic bomb|en|Atomic bomb|WD=Q650051|lt=Atomic bomb|1=Atomic bomb}} are also enshrined as deities at [[Hiroshima Gokoku Shrine]].<ref>[[護国神社#山中|山中 2013]]、154頁</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-01-20 |title=由緒 {{!}} 広島護國神社 |url=https://www.h-gokoku.or.jp/yuisho/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120233005/https://www.h-gokoku.or.jp/yuisho/ |archive-date=2021-01-20 |access-date=2022-03-08}}</ref>

The main hall burned down during the {{ill|Pacific War|en|Pacific War|WD=Q184425|lt=Pacific War|1=Pacific War}} and was reconstructed in 1959.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Takenaka |first=Akiko |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9780824856939 |title=Yasukuni Shrine |date=2017-10-16 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-5693-9 |pages=158}}</ref>

== Enshrined Deities ==
The shrine enshrines spirits of war dead from Okinawa Prefecture and mainland Japan, including civilians and student casualties who perished during the {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|en|Battle of Okinawa|WD=Q192660|lt=Battle of Okinawa|1=Battle of Okinawa}}. As of October 2005, the shrine enshrines 178,689 spirits, the highest number among {{ill|Gokoku shrines|en|Gokoku shrines|WD=Q1534477|lt=Gokoku shrines|1=Gokoku Shrines}} nationwide.

== History ==
[[File:Okinawaken_Gogoku_Shrine_torii.jpeg|thumb|right|170px|Torii gate]]
The shrine traces its origins to a {{ill|Shōkonsha|ja|招魂社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkonsha|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Shōkonsha|WD=Q11497810}} established in 1936 to honor those who died in service to Japan during conflicts such as the {{ill|First Sino-Japanese War|en|First Sino-Japanese War|WD=Q178687|lt=First Sino-Japanese War|1=First Sino-Japanese War}} and the {{ill|Russo-Japanese War|en|Russo-Japanese War|WD=Q159950|lt=Russo-Japanese War|1=Russo-Japanese War}}.<ref>加治順人『沖縄の神社』p115　ひるぎ社、2000th year 10月30日</ref> In 1940, it was designated as a Gokoku Shrine by the Ministry of Home Affairs and renamed "Okinawa Prefecture Gokoku Shrine."<ref name="x">『全國護國神社會五十年史』（1997th year 3月1日、全國護國神社會発行）287頁。</ref>

The shrine was destroyed during the {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|en|Battle of Okinawa|WD=Q192660|lt=Battle of Okinawa|1=Battle of Okinawa}} in April 1945.<ref name="x" /> A temporary shrine was constructed on April 26, 1959.<ref name="x" /> In the same year, relics of spirits from the {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|WD=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}} were transferred to the shrine, honoring mainland Japanese who died in the Battle of Okinawa. The current main shrine building was completed in October 1965, with the relocation ceremony held on November 19 and the restoration commemorative festival on November 20.<ref>加治順人『沖縄の神社』p143　ひるぎ社、2000th year 10月30日</ref><ref name="x" />

In 1980, a Kaguraden (dance hall) was added to the grounds.<ref name="x" />
